"1585","1540":"1540","9 August 1580":"9 augustus 1580","1649":"1649","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","Burton, Cheshire, England":"Burton, Cheshire, England","Cheshire":"Cheshire, England","Tarporley, Cheshire, England":"Tarporley, Cheshire, England","England":"England",", Tarporley, Cheshire, England":"Tarporley, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Aston Grange, Runcorn, Cheshire, England":"Runcorn, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1548–9 November 1602":"1548–9 November 1602","1548–1602":"1548–1602","1546–1610":"1546–1610","1580–1649":"1580–1649","1520–Male":"1520–Deceased","1523–Female":"1523–Deceased","12 Jul 1579":"12 July 1579","13 Jul 1579":"13 July 1579","1571":"1571","1580":"1580","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1602":"1602","1546":"1546","1600":"1600","1523":"1523","1610":"1610","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","6 July 1579":"6 July 1579","9 November 1602":"9 November 1602","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","9 August 1580":"9 August 1580","1649":"1649","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","Burton, Cheshire, England":"Burton, Cheshire, England","Cheshire":"Cheshire, England","Tarporley, Cheshire, England":"Tarporley, Cheshire, England","England":"England",", Tarporley, Cheshire, England":"Tarporley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Aston Grange, Runcorn, Cheshire, England":"Runcorn, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ashton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places so called, especially Ashton-under-Lyne near Manchester. Most are named from Old English <i>æsc</i> ‘ash tree’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’; the one in Northamptonshire is <i>(æt thǣm) æscum</i> ‘(at the) ash trees’. Others have been assimilated to this from different sources. The one in Devon is ‘the settlement (<i>tūn</i>) of Æschere’, while the one in Hertfordshire is ‘the settlement of Ælli’."],"variants":[{"name":"Aspden","meanings":["English: habitational name from Aspden (alias Aspen) in Oswaldtwistle, Lancashire. This surname has been confused with   Ashton   and   Austin  , and probably also with   Aston   and   Astin  , all of which are common surnames in Lancashire."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":1,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":10,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":21,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705206,"age":23,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705207,"age":37,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705208,"age":39,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705210,"age":52,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Elizabeth Ashton was born in 1548, in England, her father, John Aston, was 28 and her mother, Margaret, was 25. She married John Massey on 6 July 1579, in Tarporley, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She lived in Cheshire, England in 1579 and Tarporley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom in 1579. She was buried in Runcorn, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1548–9 November 1602":"1548–9. november 1602","1548–1602":"1548–1602","1546–1610":"1546–1610","1580–1649":"1580–1649","1520–Male":"1520–Surnud","1523–Female":"1523–Surnud","12 Jul 1579":"12. juuli 1579","13 Jul 1579":"13. juuli 1579","1571":"1571","1580":"1580","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1602":"1602","1546":"1546","1600":"1600","1523":"1523","1610":"1610","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","6 July 1579":"6. juuli 1579","9 November 1602":"9. november 1602","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","9 August 1580":"9. august 1580","1649":"1649","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","Burton, Cheshire, England":"Burton, Cheshire, England","Cheshire":"Cheshire, England","Tarporley, Cheshire, England":"Tarporley, Cheshire, England","England":"England",", Tarporley, Cheshire, England":"Tarporley, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Aston Grange, Runcorn, Cheshire, England":"Runcorn, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1548–9 November 1602":"1548–9. marraskuuta 1602","1548–1602":"1548–1602","1546–1610":"1546–1610","1580–1649":"1580–1649","1520–Male":"1520–Kuollut","1523–Female":"1523–Kuollut","12 Jul 1579":"12. heinäkuuta 1579","13 Jul 1579":"13. heinäkuuta 1579","1571":"1571","1580":"1580","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1602":"1602","1546":"1546","1600":"1600","1523":"1523","1610":"